result.execSummary:
The defendant Jacques D Winbush was found guilty of the following charge(s) in this case.

  • Possession Of A Firearm By Adjudicated Delinquent, a class G felony, Wisconsin Statutes 941.29(1m)(bm).

Notice to employers: It may be a violation of state law to discriminate against a job applicant because of an arrest or conviction record. Generally speaking, an employer may refuse to hire an applicant on the basis of a conviction only if the circumstances of the conviction substantially relate to the particular job. For more information, see Wisconsin Statute 111.335 and the Department of Workforce Development's publication, Arrest and Conviction Records under the Law.

miscConds.notes:
CONDITIONS OF EXTENDED  SUPERVISION/PROBATION:
No new violations rising to the level of probable cause.
No drugs.  No alcohol.
No contact with coactor Keon Smith including social media.
No firearms, ammunition or body armor.
Defendant to participate in alcohol and drug assessment and successfully complete recommended treatment.  Maintain absolute sobriety. Random urine screens and breathalyzer test.
Obtain and maintain employment and/or school and/or vocational training.

Defendant shall provide a DNA sample for the data bank and pay all appropriate costs.
Defendant to pay all applicable costs and surcharges and supervision fees or civil judgment will be entered.
The Court ordered that all court costs, fees, surcharges and/or restitution be paid through collection by the Department of corrections from 25% of funds under 973.05(4)(b) and as a condition of extended supervision.  Any amount remaining due and owing is subject to civil judgment and/or tax intercept or other means.

Court advised defendant that as a convicted felon he may never possess a firearm or body armor.  The Court also advised the defendant that because he was convicted of a violent felony under Section 941.29 he may not possess a firearm within 5 years of completing sentence or he will be subject to a mandatory 3 year initial confinement.

records.addlTxt:
Attorney Robert N. Meyeroff in court with Jacques D Winbush.  Attorney William T. Berens in court for State of Wisconsin. 

Defendant was advised of constitution rights and maximum penalties, waived all rights and entered a plea of GUILTY.  Defendant examined as to the plea.  Plea Questionnaire/Waiver of Rights, Addendum  and Elements/Jury Instructions, received and filed.  Stipulation by parties to complaint as a factual basis to sustain the guilty plea.  Defendant further advised that if he is not a US citizen deportation is possible.  Court found the defendant guilty as charged in the Information.  Court orders judgment of conviction entered into the record.

Statements made as to sentencing.  Additional statements made by Gloria Voss.

The Court sentenced the defendant to a MAXIMUM TERM OF IMPRISONMENT of 2 YEARS, CONCURRENT, with credit for 0 days time served; the INITIAL TERM OF CONFINEMENT in the Wisconsin State Prison System is 1 YEAR; the MAXIMUM TERM OF EXTENDED SUPERVISION is 1 YEAR.  The defendant IS eligible for the Challenge Incarceration Program (Boot Camp) and the Substance Abuse Program.  COURT STAYED THE SENTENCE and placed the defendant on probation with the State of Wisconsin, Department of Corrections for a period of 2 YEARS.

CONDITIONS OF EXTENDED SUPERVISION/PROBATION:
* Court ordered the defendant to serve 30 DAYS
   in the House of Correction.  Huber for work and/or school.  STAYED.  To be used at agent's discretion.
* No new violations rising to the level of probable cause.
* Defendant to participate in Alcohol and Drug Assessment
   and successfully complete recommended treatment.
* Maintain absolute sobriety.  No drugs.  No alcohol.
* Random urine screens and breathalyzer test.
* No contact with co-actor, Keon Smith, including social media.
* No firearms; ammunition or body armor.
* Obtain and maintain employment and/or school and/or vocational training.
* Defendant to pay all applicable costs and surcharges,
   and supervision fees or CIVIL JUDGMENT will be entered.

Defendant shall provide a DNA sample for the Data Bank and pay all appropriate costs.

Court advised defendant that his voting rights are suspended and he may not vote in any election until his civil rights are restored.  

Court advised defendant that as a convicted felon he may never possess a firearm or body armor.  The Court also advised the defendant that because he was convicted of a violent felony under Section 941.29 he may not possess a firearm within 5 years of completing sentence or he will be subject to a mandatory 3 year initial confinement.

The Court ordered that all court costs, fees, surcharges and/or restitution be paid through collection by the Department of Corrections from 25% of funds under Sec. 973.05(4)(b) and as a condition of extended supervision.  Any amount remaining due and owing is subject to civil judgment and/or tax intercept or other means.

Appeal rights given.

Filed,
Notice of Right to Seek Postconviction Relief;
Pretrial Incarceration Credit;
Ineligible Voting Notice and Acknowledgement;
Written Explanation of Determinate Sentence;
Memorandum of Conditions of Probation.
